@node fore "Foreword on the BinHex Toolkit"

@{title "ABOUT MAC FILING SYSTEM"}

Mac files consist of two parts called forks: the data fork is the most
important for non-Mac users as it contains the meaningful data, the
resource fork contains data such as program segments information, the icon
bitmap and other arbitrary data that can resemble Amiga's icon tooltypes.
Then, each Mac file has some more additional information stored in a
hidden file called the "desktop database".@{par}
Transferring such complicated files from one Mac to another without using
Mac specific media needed a way to keep together all the above
information, so BinHex was born.@{par}
This format is now so popular that Mac users use it to send their data
even to other platform users who basically need only the data fork. Even
Windows users seem to like it as their default encoding format: "it makes
bigger files so it must be good" =8-O

@{title "ABOUT BINHEX 4.0"}

BinHex 4.0 merges the original file name, the desktop database
information, the data fork and the resource fork in a single file, then
compresses repeated bytes and encodes the binary data in printable ASCII
to safely transfer it by e.g. E-Mail. It also provides an error checking
mechanism to check if the file got corrupted during the transfer.

@{title "BINHEX VS BASE64"}

BinHex is essential only when data has to be exchanged between Macs, In
all other cases Base64 encoded MIME messages can do the same things BinHex
does with less CPU overhead, less bandwidth and improved inter-platform
compatibility.

@{title "AMIGA IMPLEMENTATION"}

The BinHex Toolkit is able to preserve all the information a BinHex 4.0
file can contain:
@{par}
@{msg "FILE NAME"}: Amiga file names can be up to 30 characters in length,
Mac names can be up to 63 characters long. When importing, the BinHex
Toolkit translates the Mac character set to 7-bit ASCII, strips
unprintable characters, eventually truncates the name length to 30
characters. When exporting, the BinHex Toolkit translates the Amiga
character set to 7-bit ASCII.
@{par}
@{msg "FILE TYPE"}: The BinHex Toolkit stores (and searches) the Mac file
type in the Amiga file comment.
@{par}
@{msg "FILE CREATOR"}: The BinHex Toolkit stores (and searches) the Mac
file creator in the Amiga file comment.
@{par}
@{msg "FINDER FLAGS"}: The BinHex Toolkit stores (and searches) the Mac
Finder flags (bozo, system, bundle, invisible, locked) in the Amiga file
comment.
@{par}
@{msg "DATA AND RESOURCE FORKS"}: The BinHex Toolkit reads and writes an
Amiga file for each fork in the BinHex file.

@{title "AMIGA VS MAC"}

The BinHex Toolkit is faster, more fault tolerant, compresses better,
needs less resources, has more options than the original Mac 4.0 binary
(no kidding, I can demonstrate it).@{par}
It lacks the GUI, but it can be interfaced easily with mail and news
readers.

@endnode
@node dess "BinHex_decode (BHD) How to decode without technical knowledge"

@{title "I NEED TO DECODE A FILE CALLED MYFILE.HQX: WHAT CAN I DO?"}

"BHD" decodes (extracts data from) BinHex files, "BHE" encodes (inserts
data in) them, so the first thing to know is that you have to use "BHD"
instead of "BHE".@{par}
BinHex files may contain one or two parts called "forks": the first part
is the data fork, the second is the resource fork and BinHex files may
arbitrarily contain just the first one, just the second one or both. As
the forks must be kept separate, BHD has to create up to two output files
from a single BinHex file. A syntax like

@{par}
@{msg "bhd data=%s res=%s myfile.hqx"} ; the two %s's must be lower case
@{par}

is able to extract as many forks as possible to the current directory, the
file names will be retrieved from the BinHex archive.@{par}

you can specify the output path using this syntax:

@{par}
@{msg "bhd data=ram:%s res=ram:%s myfile.hqx"} ; %s, again, in lower case
@{par}

this extracts as many forks as possible to the ram disk, using the file
names stored in the BinHex archive.

@{par}
@{msg "bhd data=ram:donald res=ram:mickey myfile.hqx"}
@{par}

this extracts as many forks as possible to the ram disk, calling the first
one (data) "donald" and the second one (resource) "mickey".

@{par}
@{msg "bhd data=ram:out myfile.hqx"}
@{par}

this extracts only the data fork (if present) to the ram disk, calling it
"out". As the "res" (or "rsrc") parameter is missing, the resource
fork will not be extracted even if present in the BinHex file. If the data
fork is missing, bhd will extract nothing.

@{title "THINGS TO KEEP IN MIND"}

%s (lower case) in data or res arguments will be replaced by the original
file name stored in the BinHex file plus a "_d" or "_r" extension (so if
original name is "foo", data fork file name will be "foo_d" and resource
fork file name will be "foo_r").@{par}

%S (upper case) in data or res arguments will be replaced by the original
file name stored in the BinHex file (no extensions).@{par}

if you don't specify the "data" argument, the data fork will not be saved
even if present in the BinHex file. Likewise if you don't specify the
"res" (or "rsrc") argument, the resource fork will not be saved even if
present in the BinHex file.@{par}

missing forks will generate no output file (so if a BinHex file contains
only the data fork and you set the "res" parameter but not the "data"
parameter, bhd will extract nothing).

@endnode
@node deqa "BinHex_decode (BHD) Answers to decoding problems"

@{title "GENERAL"}
@{que "BHD extracts nothing. Why"}
@{ans "You didn't specify the DATA/K and/or RES=RSRC/K arguments"}
BHD can extract a whole BinHex file or just a part. If you don't specify
the "data" argument, the data fork will not be saved even if present in
the BinHex file. Likewise if you don't specify the "res" (or "rsrc")
argument, the resource fork will not be saved even if present in the
BinHex file.

@{que "Wrong! I set one (or both) and BHD keeps extracting nothing. Why"}
@{ans "The fork you wish to extract is missing"}
BHD is designed not to create empty files. If you specify the "data"
argument but the data fork is missing in the BinHex file, no data will be
saved. Likewise if you specify the "res" (or "rsrc") argument but the
resource fork is missing in the BinHex file, no resource will be saved.
If you set both the arguments and BHD keeps extracting nothing, then
somebody sent you a malformed BinHex file or encoded you a empty file.

@{title "SHAPESHIFTER"}
@{que "The finder tries to open any file I decoded with TeachText. Why"}
@{ans "You didn't specify the NOTE/S switch"}
Mac-handler stores the Mac file types in the Amiga file comments, if you
save a file without file comment, mac-handler will choose "plain text" as
default file type. Using the "note" switch you enable BHD to set the
correct file comment to all files it creates, as a consequence the finder
will correctly recognize the files you decoded.

@{que "I set the NOTE/S switch, but the programs I decode don't start. Why"}
@{ans "It's a matter of MacControl"}
You have to save the data fork on the mac-hadler dos device after a
"MacControl <device:> data", then you have to save the resource fork on
the mac-handler dos device with the exact same name you used to save the
data fork, but after a "MacControl <device:> rsrc". Also don't forget to
specify the "note" switch in BHD command line. If you save the data fork
when in "data" MacControl mode and save the resource fork when in "rsrc"
MacControl mode all should work.

@{que "This is too complicated. Is there a simpler way"}
@{ans "You can write a script, something like this"}
.key FROM/A,TO/A@{par}
.bra {@{par}
.ket }@{par}
maccontrol data "{to}"@{par}
bhd note data="{to}" res=t:bhdtemp_$process "{from}"@{par}
maccontrol rsrc "{to}"@{par}
copy clone t:bhdtemp_$process "{to}"@{par}
maccontrol data "{to}"@{par}
delete quiet t:bhdtemp_$process

@{que "I don't like scripts. Have you other ideas"}
@{ans "You can mount Mac dos devices twice"}
You can create two equal mountlists for each dos device you wish to mount,
just call them the same way except the first letter that has to be "D" in
one and "R" in the other (exaple: DMAC0: RMAC0:). mount both dos devices,
then issue a "MacControl rsrc rmac0:" once. Now you have simultaneous
access to the data and resource forks of a same drive, so "BHD note
data=dmac0:%S res=rmac0:%S <yourfile.hqx>" (%S have to be upper case) will
extract correctly to a mac dos device any BinHex archive.

@{title "ERROR MESSAGES"}
@{que "BHD says mydata.hqx is not a hqx7 file, but I'm sure it is. Why"}
@{ans "There may be a case or a indentation problem in the source text"}
Check that the "(This file must be converted with BinHex 4.0)" line exists
and has the parentheses, is correctly spelled, the characters are in the
correct case and there are no extra spaces, tabulators or non-breaking
spaces (ASCII code 160). Also check that the header string and the first
encoded line are not indented and are separated by at least a "new line"
character (ASCII CR or LF). At last check that the first character of the
first encoded line and the last character of the last line are a ":".

@endnode
@node deqr "BinHex_decode (BHD) Quick reference"

BHD stands for BinHex Decoder, it accepts a BinHex 4.0 encoded file and
generates up to two files containing the data and resource forks.

@{title "REQUIREMENTS"}

BHD runs under Kickstart 2.0 and above from any Shell (it does not support
Workbench directly) on any Amiga, it needs at least 4 Kb of stack memory
and at least about 25 Kb of free memory.

@{title "COMMAND LINE ARGUMENTS"}

@{cli "INFILE/A"}
This required argument is the name of the input file (wildcards are not
supported). The file must be in BinHex format.

@{cli "DATA/K"}
This keyword argument designates the file name where the data fork will be
stored. If the argument contains a "%S" token (without quotes), the token
will be replaced with the filename stored in the BinHex file. If the
argument contains a "%s" token (without quotes), the token will be
replaced with the filename stored in the BinHex file plus a "_d" suffix.
If you don't specify this argument, no data fork will be saved.

@{cli "RES=RSRC/K"}
This keyword argument designates the file name where the resource fork
will be stored. If the argument contains a "%S" token (without quotes),
the token will be replaced with the filename stored in the BinHex file.
If the argument contains a "%s" token (without quotes), the token will be
replaced with the filename stored in the BinHex file plus a "_r" suffix.
If you don't specify this argument, no resource fork will be saved.

@{cli "BUFSIZE/K/N"}
This keyword numeric argument designates the size in bytes of each work
buffer. The buffers are 3 and equal in size, allocated in a contiguous
chunk of memory. Minimum value is 8192, maximum value depends on the
largest free memory chunk in your system, default size for each buffer is
16 Kb.

@{cli "NOTE/S"}
If this switch is set then each output file will be commented with the
file type, the file creator and the Finder flags.
See also the @{" file comment format " link tech} chapter.

@{title "OPERATION"}

INFILE does not need to start with a BinHex header string, BHD will scan
the whole file until it finds one. If INFILE contains more BinHex
documents, only the first one will be extracted.@{par}
@{par}
The data and resource forks will be extracted only if their name has been
specified by the DATA/K,RES=RSRC/K arguments: in this way you can
extract only the forks you really need (most of the times the data one).
BHD will never create empty files: if you need empty files, you can
generate a couple of empty files and let BHD overwrite them.@{par}
@{par}
Using a large (100 Kb or more) BUFSIZE can improve decoding time when
reading or writing large files from CD-Rom's or similar relatively slow
media, but it needs much memory and uses intensively the CPU for larger
time intervals.@{par}
@{par}
The NOTE switch allows to write the output files directly on Mac media
(such as ShapeShifter's mac-handler) or simply to preserve the Mac file
attributes for a future re-encoding: it comments the output files with
the type/creator pair followed by the active Finder flags. Should the
type/creator pair be invalid, the ????/???? default pair will be used.

@{title "ERROR MESSAGES"}

BHD shows the standard AmigaDOS messages on its standard output in case of
file I/O error, memory allocation failure or wrong command line arguments.
BHD will set return code to FAIL (20) if something goes wrong, ERROR (10)
if command line options are wrong, OK (0) if all goes flawlessly.

@{cli "[INFILE]: not a hqx7 file"}
Infile hasn't the BinHex header string "(This file must be converted with
BinHex 4.0)" or its data does not start with a ":", or the header string
is not separated by at least a "end of line" character (ASCII CR or LF)
from the encoded data, or the file header and data are indented from the
left margin.@{par}
You can recover the file removing the indentation in front of the header
line and the first data line, or adding the missing header string, ":" or
end-of-line characters.

@{cli "[INFILE]: unexpected end of file"}
Infile hasn't a ":" character at the end of its data chunk. If you add
one by hand after the last data character and then you get a CRC error,
then the file really got truncated and there is no way to recover lost
data.

@{cli "crc error in [HEAD|DATA|RSRC] (expected [XXXX], found [YYYY])"}
If the CRC error is in the BinHex header no extraction will be attempted.
If the CRC error is in the forks, corrupted forks will not be deleted.

@endnode
@node enss "BinHex_encode (BHE) How to encode without technical knowledge"

@{title "I NEED TO ENCODE A FILE CALLED MYDATA: WHAT CAN I DO?"}

"BHE" encodes (inserts data in) BinHex files, "BHD" decodes (extracts data
from) them, so the first thing to know is that you have to use "BHE"
instead of "BHD".@{par}
BinHex files may contain one or two parts called "forks": the first part
is the data fork, the second is the resource fork and BinHex files may
arbitrarily contain just the first one, just the second one or both. As
the forks must be kept separate, BHE has to read up to two input files to
generate a single BinHex file. A syntax like

@{par}
@{msg "bhe data=mydata sendme.hqx"}
@{par}

encodes the data contained in the "mydata" file in the first fork (data)
of a BinHex file called "sendme.hqx".

@{par}
@{msg "bhe data=mydata res=mac-only sendme.hqx"}
@{par}

encodes the data contained in the "mydata" file in the first fork (data),
then encodes the data contained in the "mac-only" file in the last fork
(resource) of a BinHex file called "sendme.hqx".

@{par}
@{msg "bhe res=mac-only sendme.hqx"}
@{par}

encodes the data contained in the "mac-only" file in the last fork
(resource) of a BinHex file called "sendme.hqx".

@{title "THINGS TO KEEP IN MIND"}

Images, sound, text or whatever you have to encode always need to be put
in the data fork or Mac users will not be able to read them. If you have
to send two files, create two BinHex archives.@{par}

In the resource fork you can only put real Mac resource forks, any
other kind of data will be lost on real Macs.@{par}

When Mac users wish to extract the data you encoded, they will be prompted
for a default file name that was stored in the BinHex file by BHE.
BHE stores the name of the Amiga output file name (sendme, in this case)
without any three letters extension the name may have.@{par}

@endnode
@node enqa "BinHex_encode (BHE) Answers to encoding problems"

@{title "GENERAL"}
@{que "Which is the right fork for my data files"}
@{ans "Only the data one"}
The resource fork can only contain resources created by a Mac, no
arbitrary data should be put there. Leave blank the resource fork if you
don't have a resource to encode.

@{que "I have a real resource here, may I encode it in the data fork"}
@{ans "No"}
Simply leave blank the data fork if your resource hasn't related data.

@{que "Is resource fork needed for my sounds/images/text/other"}
@{ans "No"}
Any file of any kind (except Mac programs) created with your Amiga does
not need any resource fork.

@{que "Can I add or remove forks from a BinHex file"}
@{ans "Not directly"}
You'll need to decode and re-encode your BinHex file.

@{title "SHAPESHIFTER"}
@{que "How can I encode straight from a mac-handler dos device"}
@{ans "It's a matter of MacControl"}
You have to read the data fork from the mac-hadler dos device after a
"MacControl <device:> data", then you have to read the resource fork from
the mac-handler dos device but after a "MacControl <device:> rsrc". If you
read the data fork when in "rsrc" MacControl mode and/or read the
resource fork when in "data" MacControl mode, the BinHex file will contain
correctly encoded but corrupted data.

@{que "This is too complicated. Is there a simpler way"}
@{ans "You can write a script, something like this"}
.key FROM/A,TO/A@{par}
.bra {@{par}
.ket }@{par}
maccontrol data "{from}"@{par}
copy "{from}" t:bhetemp_$process@{par}
maccontrol rsrc "{from}"@{par}
bhe data=t:bhetemp_$process res="{from}" "{to}"@{par}
maccontrol data "{from}"@{par}
delete quiet t:bhetemp_$process

@{que "I don't like scripts. Have you other ideas"}
@{ans "You can mount Mac dos devices twice"}
You can create two equal mountlists for each dos device you wish to mount,
just call them the same way except the first letter that has to be "D" in
one and "R" in the other (exaple: DMAC0: RMAC0:). mount both dos devices,
then issue a "MacControl rsrc rmac0:" once. Now you have simultaneous
access to the data and resource forks of a same drive, so "BHE
data=dmac0:<filename> res=rmac0:<samename> <binhexfile.hqx>" will create a
BinHex archive straight from any mac dos device.

@{title "PROBLEMS ON MAC"}
@{que "The finder does not recognize the file types of what I encode. Why"}
@{ans "There is a problem in the source file comments"}
Be sure that at least one of the fork files on your Amiga has a valid
@{" file comment " link tech}.

@endnode
@node enqr "BinHex_encode (BHE) Quick reference"

BHE stands for BinHex Encoder, it generates a BinHex 4.0 encoded file
reading up to two files containing the data and resource forks.

@{title "REQUIREMENTS"}

BHE runs under Kickstart 2.0 and above from any Shell (it does not support
Workbench directly) on any Amiga, it needs at least 4 Kb of stack memory
and at least about 25 Kb of free memory.

@{title "COMMAND LINE ARGUMENTS"}

@{cli "OUTFILE/A"}
This required argument is the name of the BinHex output file.

@{cli "DATA/K"}
This keyword argument designates the file name containing the data fork.
If you don't specify this argument no data fork will be added.@{par}
See also the @{" file comment format " link tech} chapter.

@{cli "RES=RSRC/K"}
This keyword argument designates the file name containing the resource
fork. If you don't specify this argument no resource fork will be
added.@{par}
See also the @{" file comment format " link tech} chapter.

@{cli "BUFSIZE/K/N"}
This keyword numeric argument designates the size in bytes of each work
buffer. The buffers are 3 and equal in size, allocated in a contiguous
chunk of memory. Minimum value is 8192, maximum value depends on the
largest free memory chunk in your system, default size for each buffer is
16 Kb.

@{cli "NOTE/S"}
If this switch is set then the output file will be commented "TEXT/BNHQ".
See also the @{" file comment format " link tech} chapter.

@{cli "MIME/S"}
If this switch is set then the appropriate MIME header will be prepended
to the BinHex header string.

@{cli "CR/S"}
If this switch is set then each line will be terminated by a Carriage
Return character (Mac end of line marker) instead of a Line Feed character
(Amiga end of line marker).

@{cli "APPEND/S"}
If this switch is set then the data generated by the program will be
stored starting at the end of the already existing outfile instead of
overwriting the outfile.

@{title "OPERATION"}

The OUTFILE/A value will be used also as the default BinHex file name. It
will be stored in the BinHex header in 7 bit ASCII format, if the value
has a 3 characters extension to the right, the extension will be stripped
(examples of such extensions may be: ".out", ".hqx", ".mac", or any other
string starting with a "." followed by 3 characters) so a outfile named
"Test.hqx" will save the data in a file called "Test.hqx" and will
generate the "Test" default BinHex file name, and a outfile named
"Test.hqx7" will save the data in a file called "Test.hqx7" and will
generate the "Test.hqx7" default BinHex file name.@{par}
@{par}
The data and resource forks will be saved only if their name has been
specified by the DATA/K,RES=RSRC/K arguments: in this way you can
generate BinHex files containing just one fork without creating empty
files.@{par}
@{par}
The NOTE and CR switches are designed to write directly the output file
directly on Mac media (such as ShapeShifter's mac-handler).@{par}
@{par}
The MIME and APPEND switches can be used when invoking BHE from scripts
to compose E-Mail bodies, note that the MIME name preserves the 3
characters file name extension if present.@{par}
@{par}
Using a large (100 Kb or more) BUFSIZE can improve encoding time when
reading or writing large files from CD-Rom's or similar relatively slow
media, but it needs much memory and uses intensively the CPU for larger
time intervals. @{par}
@{par}
When getting the desktop database information from the file comment,
Finder flags will be OR-combined, so if a flag is present in the data fork
file comment and another flag is present in the resource fork comment, the
resulting BinHex header will contain both flags.@{par}
When getting file type and file creator from file comments, BHE tries to
use the ones stored in the data file comment, if the data file is not
specified, not found, or its comment is not set, BHE will check the
resource fork file, if the resource file is not specified, not found,
or its comment is not set, a default ????/???? type/creator pair will be
set in the BinHex header.

@{title "ERROR MESSAGES"}

BHE shows the standard AmigaDOS messages on its standard output in case of
file I/O error, memory allocation failure or wrong command line arguments.
BHE will set return code to FAIL (20) if something goes wrong, ERROR (10)
if command line options are wrong, OK (0) if all goes flawlessly.

@endnode
@node tech "Technical matters"

@{title "FILE COMMENT FORMAT"}

File comment contains strings separated by white spaces.
The first string that is 9 characters long and has a "/" character in the
middle will be considered the file type/creator pair, if the 5th character
of the comment string is a "/" then no further check will be made and the
first 9 characters of the comment will be considered the type/creator
pair (so that type and creator may contain spaces).@{par}
All the 3 characters long strings will be (case insensitively) matched with
"loc", "inv", "bun", "sys", "boz" to set active the "locked", "invisible",
"bundle", "system" and "bozo" Finder flags.

@{title "WHAT FINDER FLAGS NEED TO BE SET"}

Leave them unset, as they may sound familiar they are not. The only
purpose BHD stores those flags in the file comment is to allow BHE to
rebuild the same BinHex file BHD decoded...

@endnode
@node hist "History of the BinHex Toolkit"
@next hist

@{title "DEVELOPMENT"}

I write and test the BinHex Toolkit on an A3000/030-25, Before releasing
each new version to the public I test the program under Enforcer and
Mungwall on Kickstart 3.1.

@{title "PERSONAL"}

Greetings to all who e-mailed me to pay a compliment to my BinHex toolkit,
I really appreciated it!@{par}
Apologies to all who e-mailed me complaining about the cryptic command
line syntax, I hope you overcame all the difficulties.

@{title "BHD RELEASE HISTORY"}
@{rev "BHD 37.01 (10-Oct-96)" "First"}
@{msg "BUG"}: BHD can't accept more than one "%s" token for each output
file name format string but it does not check for multiple tokens.

@{rev "BHD 37.02 (18-Oct-96)" "Second"}
@{msg "BUGFIX"}: v37.01 failed with "not an hqx7 file" error if the BinHex
header was not found within the first BUFSIZE/K/N bytes of the
INFILE/A.@{par}
@{msg "BUGFIX"}: v37.01 had a flacky "%s" token interpreter. I rewrote
the token handling routine, now it ignores extra "%s" tokens.@{par}
@{msg "ADDED"}: "%s" token is replaced with default BinHex name plus "_d"
or "_r". "%S" token is replaced with plain default BinHex name.

@{rev "BHD 37.03 (31-Oct-96)" "Third"}
@{msg "BUGFIX"}: I didn't interpret the BinHex documentation in the right
way and I assumed that no CRC was saved for missing/empty forks. 37.02
extracts bad resource forks when data fork is empty and hqx file is not
created by BHE 37.02. As 37.02 will be deleted from Aminet as soon as I
upload this new version, I added @{" here " link reco} a copy for recovery
purposes only.@{par}
@{msg "CHANGED"}: added a "bad template" error message if neither
DATA/K or RES=RSRC/K is specified.

@{rev "BHD 37.04 (12-Dec-96)" "Fourth"}
@{msg "ADDED"}: now BHD can be interrupted by sending it a CTRL_C break
signal (any file created by BHD will not be automatically deleted).


@{title "BHE RELEASE HISTORY"}
@{rev "BHE 37.01 (10-Oct-96)" "First"}
@{msg "BUG"}: file comment interpreter does not support spaces in
type/creator strings.

@{rev "BHE 37.02 (18-Oct-96)" "Second"}
@{msg "CHANGED"}: made a smarter file comment parser, type/creator can now
contain spaces if the type/creator string starts at the beginning of the
file comment.

@{rev "BHE 37.03 (31-Oct-96)" "Third"}
@{msg "BUGFIX"}: I didn't interpret the BinHex documentation in the right
way and I assumed that no CRC was to be saved for missing/empty forks.
37.02 creates hqx files that can be extracted only with BHD 37.02 if data
fork is empty.@{par}
@{msg "CHANGED"}: added a "bad template" error message if neither
DATA/K or RES=RSRC/K is specified.

@{rev "BHE 37.04 (12-Dec-96)" "Fourth"}
@{msg "ADDED"}: now BHE can be interrupted by sending it a CTRL_C break
signal (the file created by BHE will not be automatically deleted).

@endnode
@node reco "BHD 37.02 binary"
@prev hist
@next hist

